WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.800
Welcome to the Data Science Hangout, hope everybody's having a great week.

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:20.240
If we haven't met before, I'm Rachel Dempsey, I lead our pro community at Posit.

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:24.520
Before I forget to say this, I want to share an exciting announcement that the call for

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:31.840
talks at Posit conference in Chicago in September was extended to April 7th, so you have a little

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:34.240
bit more time to procrastinate.

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:42.240
So if anybody wants to submit a talk, I'll put the updated blog post into the chat here

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:43.240
too.

00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:45.279
But thanks again for joining us today.

00:00:45.279 --> 00:00:50.560
The Data Science Hangout is our open space to chat about data science leadership, questions

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:54.720
you're facing, and getting to hear about what's going on in the world of data across

00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:56.360
different industries.

00:00:56.360 --> 00:01:01.720
And so if you are watching this on YouTube in the future, in our future world, it happens

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:07.279
every Thursday at the same time, same place, so you can add it to your calendar with the

00:01:07.279 --> 00:01:09.879
details that would be below in the YouTube.

00:01:09.879 --> 00:01:14.559
But every week we feature a different data science leader as my co-host to help lead

00:01:14.559 --> 00:01:18.480
our discussion and answer questions from you all.

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:23.040
Together at the Hangout, we're all dedicated to making this a welcoming environment for

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:24.040
everybody.

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:29.680
We love when everybody can participate, no matter your level of experience or industry

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:31.320
or area of work.

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:34.919
It is totally okay to just listen in too.

00:01:34.919 --> 00:01:38.239
There's always three ways, though, that you could jump in and ask questions or provide

00:01:38.239 --> 00:01:39.559
your own perspective.

00:01:39.559 --> 00:01:46.260
So you can jump in by raising your hand here on Zoom, and I'll look out for it.

00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:51.379
You can put questions in the Zoom chat, and feel free to put a little star next to it

00:01:51.379 --> 00:01:54.459
if you wanted me to read it, if you're in a coffee shop or something.

00:01:54.459 --> 00:01:59.059
Otherwise, I'll just call on you to jump in and introduce yourself.

00:01:59.059 --> 00:02:03.900
And then third, we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously.

00:02:03.900 --> 00:02:09.419
And I believe Hannah and Tyler will be sharing that, yep, in the chat in just a second.

00:02:09.419 --> 00:02:13.380
Thank you so much again for joining us, and thank you, Dan.

00:02:13.380 --> 00:02:18.979
Dan Negre is Director of Analytics at MarketBridge and is joining as our co-host today.

00:02:18.979 --> 00:02:24.179
Dan, I'd love to have you jump in and introduce yourself and maybe share a little bit about

00:02:24.179 --> 00:02:27.940
your role and also something you like to do outside of work.

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:28.940
Sure.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:32.020
Thanks, Rachel, and thanks for having me here today.

00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:34.179
I was super excited about it when you reached out.

00:02:34.179 --> 00:02:35.179
I was thrilled.

00:02:35.179 --> 00:02:37.500
I love talking about this stuff.

00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:41.899
So as Rachel mentioned, I'm Director of Analytics at MarketBridge.

00:02:41.899 --> 00:02:49.539
We're a – we call ourselves a go-to-market science company, and so we really use reproducible

00:02:49.539 --> 00:02:57.580
scientific methods to tackle our clients' toughest measurement problems in sales and marketing.

00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:09.259
My role is – I wear a lot of hats, but I guess primarily I'm focused on our – sort

00:03:09.259 --> 00:03:14.259
of our tooling and our approach to, like, building tools that we can apply across different

00:03:14.259 --> 00:03:20.699
problems as well as some of the front-end stuff we do with Shiny and serving up insights

00:03:20.699 --> 00:03:25.339
to clients based on the models we build.

00:03:25.339 --> 00:03:28.899
I'm sure we'll get into more questions about some of that, but I'm from Cleveland, Ohio.

00:03:28.899 --> 00:03:34.940
I live right outside of Cleveland, and outside of work, I love playing basketball.

00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:35.940
Awesome.

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:39.020
Thank you, Dan.

00:03:39.779 --> 00:03:44.779
So to kind of put us in your mindset of the problems that you're helping to solve, what's

00:03:44.779 --> 00:03:52.220
an example of a marketing use case or maybe a problem you've helped a stakeholder with?

00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:53.580
Sure.

00:03:53.580 --> 00:04:00.539
Probably the most, you know, common problem that we work on that every company is challenged

00:04:00.539 --> 00:04:04.899
with is measuring their marketing effectiveness or, you know, you think about all the different

00:04:04.899 --> 00:04:08.619
efforts you do from a marketing perspective, reaching out to customers directly through

00:04:08.619 --> 00:04:15.500
different channels, direct mail, email, phone, spending money on paid ads on, you know,

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:18.619
various social media channels and paid search and all that kind of stuff.

00:04:18.619 --> 00:04:26.739
So we help our clients measure those efforts effectively and in a way that doesn't double

00:04:26.739 --> 00:04:30.019
count or sort of over-attribute.

00:04:30.019 --> 00:04:36.019
So we've got some very smart approaches to these sorts of problems and some very creative

00:04:36.019 --> 00:04:41.459
ways to address them.

00:04:41.459 --> 00:04:47.019
So maybe these could be related, but I know on past Hangouts, we've talked a lot about

00:04:47.019 --> 00:04:48.019
like community.

00:04:48.019 --> 00:04:54.579
And so, for example, like an internal meetup and being able to show like the value of that

00:04:54.579 --> 00:05:00.220
within your own organization, do you have some tips for people here who might be trying

00:05:00.220 --> 00:05:02.420
to do that?

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:09.660
Well, I would say, you know, without getting, you know, too into the weeds in some of this

00:05:09.660 --> 00:05:15.299
stuff, try to think of the problems as in more broad ways.

00:05:15.299 --> 00:05:17.859
It's like, what is your goal?

00:05:17.859 --> 00:05:23.700
Like is your goal to, you know, by having internal meetups, is your goal to get like

00:05:23.700 --> 00:05:24.700
what's your objective?

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:26.220
What's your measurable objective on the back end?

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:31.179
Are you trying to get more people to register for these events going forward?

00:05:31.179 --> 00:05:36.899
Or, you know, is it more of a softer lead type of thing to get people to sign up for

00:05:36.899 --> 00:05:37.899
the conference?

00:05:37.899 --> 00:05:44.299
And, you know, just using Posit as an example, but, you know, think about the problem holistically

00:05:44.299 --> 00:05:49.220
before we start like diving into pulling data and arranging data and all that stuff.

00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:53.779
Because the more you can think about it, the bigger picture of what's going on, the more

00:05:53.779 --> 00:06:00.700
you'll be able to, you know, one, explain what you're doing to other people, but also,

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:05.299
you know, think about how all the different pieces that affect what you're trying to measure

00:06:05.299 --> 00:06:09.859
can kind of come into play and work together with each other.

00:06:09.859 --> 00:06:12.380
Thank you.

00:06:12.380 --> 00:06:17.820
So, I get to ask you all the questions right in the beginning as we're thinking of the

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:22.779
ones that as people are thinking of their own, but I know you said you use Shiny a bit,

00:06:22.779 --> 00:06:27.019
so I'd love to hear a little bit more about how you're using Shiny today.

00:06:27.019 --> 00:06:28.019
Sure.

00:06:28.019 --> 00:06:33.820
So, first of all, I'm a huge fan, and I've been following the product, I guess you'd

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:36.779
call it product, along since it first launched.

00:06:36.779 --> 00:06:41.019
I knew it was going to be a game changer, because at the time you could already do some

00:06:41.019 --> 00:06:49.100
really incredible stuff visually with R. And the moment I saw how the Reactive Framework

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:53.899
worked and how to manipulate things and have it, you know, change what users were looking

00:06:53.899 --> 00:06:55.299
at, I knew it was going to be awesome.

00:06:55.299 --> 00:07:00.579
So, I've spent a lot of time in the last seven or eight years, I can't remember how long

00:07:00.579 --> 00:07:06.940
it's been, trying to get better and trying to learn the ins and outs of Shiny.

00:07:06.940 --> 00:07:13.619
But at the end of the day, like, I look at it like, your ability to create in a tool

00:07:13.619 --> 00:07:15.540
like R is pretty limitless.

00:07:15.859 --> 00:07:19.779
There are so many, like, I compare it to, like, Legos, right?

00:07:19.779 --> 00:07:21.380
There's all sorts of cool Lego sets out there.

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:25.660
You think of a package maybe as a Lego set, and the fact that you can just pull from different

00:07:25.660 --> 00:07:32.579
packages and you can kind of create your own original Lego creation from all these different,

00:07:32.579 --> 00:07:35.820
you know, really strong and stable parts that come underneath them.

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:39.299
So, as soon as you kind of accept that, and then you think how Shiny can kind of take

00:07:39.299 --> 00:07:45.459
that to the next level, you're kind of giving your users the ability to take your Legos

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:50.140
and rearrange them in different ways and do some cool stuff with it.

00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:57.380
So, now to talk a little bit more about actual work-related stuff and not Legos, but...

00:07:57.380 --> 00:08:00.380
I like the Legos explanation, that's helpful.

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:04.779
Yeah, with what we do, you know, I think about building marketing measurement or marketing

00:08:04.779 --> 00:08:12.779
mix models, when we can serve those up to our clients and have them change the data

00:08:12.779 --> 00:08:15.940
around that they are scoring those models on.

00:08:15.940 --> 00:08:20.059
Maybe they're making assumptions around how they might spend differently next quarter

00:08:20.059 --> 00:08:24.339
on a certain channel, or maybe their budget's going to be reduced and they need to scale

00:08:24.339 --> 00:08:25.339
things back.

00:08:25.339 --> 00:08:30.739
They can rescore the models, and all that's happening, you know, in the Reactive backend.

00:08:30.739 --> 00:08:36.219
You know, they're making, using some inputs to change assumptions around the data, and

00:08:36.219 --> 00:08:41.820
then having the models get rescored, and someone pointed something about Duplo's there.

00:08:41.859 --> 00:08:43.260
But, yeah, that's a lot of it.

00:08:43.260 --> 00:08:50.700
You know, seeing visuals get regenerated that show, you know, time series plots or tables

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:56.859
that have summarized data, that's a lot of what we're doing, you know, manipulating those

00:08:56.859 --> 00:09:01.500
models on the backend and, you know, rescoring them and showing results in different ways.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:02.500
Awesome.

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:06.700
Alan, I see you just asked a question in the chat.

00:09:06.700 --> 00:09:07.700
Do you want to jump in here?

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:08.700
Yeah, sure.

00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:09.700
Hi, Dan.

00:09:09.780 --> 00:09:13.739
I've been learning a little bit about some of what our teams are doing with marketing

00:09:13.739 --> 00:09:18.020
effectiveness measurement lately, and it's an interesting space, and there's a ton of

00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:19.580
challenges and stuff to learn.

00:09:19.580 --> 00:09:23.299
So, this is timely and fun to sort of get to learn from you a little bit.

00:09:23.299 --> 00:09:27.140
I'm curious if you can talk a little bit about your team and what the roles are there, and

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:31.500
maybe say a little bit more about, are you, as a director, are you leading people, or

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:36.219
is your leadership in a more of a kind of technical space, or like a mix, and how you

00:09:36.219 --> 00:09:37.219
find that balance?

00:09:37.219 --> 00:09:38.219
Sure.

00:09:38.219 --> 00:09:39.219
Great question.

00:09:39.739 --> 00:09:44.900
So, my role is in a little bit more of a technical space.

00:09:44.900 --> 00:09:48.380
We do have a good structure to our team, though.

00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:55.780
I think, you know, we've kind of, it's a little tough to describe because it's a mixture of,

00:09:55.780 --> 00:10:00.500
you know, sort of flat, but also with specialty.

00:10:00.500 --> 00:10:04.859
So, we know we have, and this is an important thing I was hoping to bring up at some point

00:10:04.859 --> 00:10:11.820
in this conversation, but, you know, we, where I've seen teams kind of fail or not

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:17.340
succeed as well is when, you know, people are trying to, there's like a single role

00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:21.299
that, you know, leadership has in mind, and everyone has to fit into that role.

00:10:21.299 --> 00:10:22.700
And that's not the case that we have here.

00:10:22.700 --> 00:10:27.859
You know, we have people that are really good with theoretical statistics, and we have people

00:10:27.859 --> 00:10:33.820
that are really good with, you know, data storage and data storage solutions and data

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:35.580
engineering, I guess.

00:10:35.580 --> 00:10:39.380
We have people that are good with Shiny, and we have people good with data visualization.

00:10:39.380 --> 00:10:46.659
So, what we try to do is, it involves a lot of communication, too, and breaking projects

00:10:46.659 --> 00:10:52.739
down into individual components where we can say who fits best on those components so that

00:10:52.739 --> 00:10:58.380
we can get the best out of everybody while also giving exposure to different components

00:10:58.380 --> 00:11:00.140
so people can learn in different areas.

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:07.700
So, recognizing those differences and trying to get the most out of people's expertise

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:08.700
is huge for that.

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:18.500
I see there was an anonymous question that goes back to us talking about Shiny, and it

00:11:18.500 --> 00:11:22.739
said, do you think that the main value that R provides is Shiny?

00:11:22.739 --> 00:11:29.260
And this person said, personally, I find the emphasis on, the overemphasis on Shiny sometimes

00:11:29.380 --> 00:11:33.580
makes R seem like a limited language, and was curious to get your thoughts on that.

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:36.580
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:37.580
That's a good point.

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:47.020
I don't see it that way because, I mean, I've been using R for a long time and have seen

00:11:47.020 --> 00:11:48.580
it kind of evolve.

00:11:48.580 --> 00:11:54.500
So, obviously, I think, it wasn't by much, but I believe R Markdown preceded the release

00:11:54.500 --> 00:11:55.500
of Shiny.

00:11:55.739 --> 00:11:58.380
So, that was pretty innovative at the time.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:02.340
You could, you know, you could create reports in all sorts of different formats and embed

00:12:02.340 --> 00:12:03.340
output and code.

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:06.539
And so, that is still a great use case.

00:12:06.539 --> 00:12:12.700
In fact, that's one of the things when I'm talking to clients and, you know, in best

00:12:12.700 --> 00:12:16.580
case scenario, we have clients that can log into our environment and see some of the cool

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:17.979
stuff we create in our environment.

00:12:17.979 --> 00:12:21.739
But there are other cases when, you know, just by, I'm sure everybody on the phone here

00:12:21.739 --> 00:12:25.539
has been in a situation where they've had to work in a different computing environment

00:12:25.539 --> 00:12:28.539
without all the resources that they would love to have at their disposal.

00:12:28.539 --> 00:12:31.340
So, we find ourselves in that situation sometimes.

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:37.580
And when we're fortunate enough to have even like the ability to install RStudio Desktop

00:12:37.580 --> 00:12:43.260
or something, your ability to create those types of reports now becomes on the table.

00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:48.940
And one thing that I think gets overlooked a lot is all the really cool and somewhat

00:12:48.940 --> 00:12:53.059
interactive visualizations you can do in R Markdown output.

00:12:53.059 --> 00:12:57.380
You know, I'm a huge fan of those, the HTML widgets collection of packages.

00:12:57.380 --> 00:13:03.219
So like DT for tables and Leaflet for maps and digraphs for time series plots and things

00:13:03.219 --> 00:13:04.219
like that.

00:13:04.219 --> 00:13:09.299
A lot of clients and companies you might work with may have never even seen something like

00:13:09.299 --> 00:13:10.299
that before.

00:13:10.299 --> 00:13:15.900
They might not even know that they could get a static document that has an embedded map

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:21.380
with icons for individual lat long coordinates and polygons for shapes.

00:13:21.380 --> 00:13:26.659
And, you know, they did hover over to see different information at different, you know,

00:13:26.659 --> 00:13:27.659
regions.

00:13:27.659 --> 00:13:30.739
So, those have gone a long way, right?

00:13:30.739 --> 00:13:36.059
I mean, they've gone a long way with clients that have been received very well.

00:13:36.059 --> 00:13:40.140
And that obviously stops short of shiny reactivity.

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:46.940
But then even just as a, you know, as an exploratory or language to explore data, manipulate

00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:51.859
data, generate plots in the viewer, even pacing those into PowerPoint, even if they're, you

00:13:51.859 --> 00:13:54.219
know, static plots can go a long way.

00:13:54.219 --> 00:14:00.099
And of course, building models and generating insights around, you know, inferential statistics

00:14:00.099 --> 00:14:01.099
as well.

00:14:01.099 --> 00:14:02.099
Absolutely.

00:14:02.099 --> 00:14:09.539
I think also, like, we talk about shiny apps a lot in the visualizations because it's fun

00:14:09.539 --> 00:14:14.780
to talk about the things that are created and, like, things that people are actually

00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:17.700
using and interacting with.

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:22.059
A question, I'm not sure if I'm going to frame this question the right way or if I fully

00:14:22.059 --> 00:14:23.059
thought about it.

00:14:23.059 --> 00:14:31.099
But I, so, I read the book Checklist Manifesto, and I've been thinking about, like, if there

00:14:31.099 --> 00:14:38.659
may be some sort of checklist for, like, providing value to an organization, like, or a way for

00:14:38.780 --> 00:14:43.780
your team to, like, best impact the business with data science.

00:14:43.780 --> 00:14:49.580
And I was wondering if there's something that comes to mind for you, like, something that

00:14:49.580 --> 00:14:54.900
you say, like, oh, you definitely need to have this to provide the impact on the business.

00:14:54.900 --> 00:15:00.140
Let me think about that because it was a little bit, a little bit.

00:15:00.140 --> 00:15:07.020
Yeah, I'm still, like, forming what I want that question to be.

00:15:07.020 --> 00:15:14.500
Like, a tip for all of us on impacting the business with data science.

00:15:14.500 --> 00:15:24.900
So I think if every business is going to have KPIs, and there's going to be other metrics

00:15:24.900 --> 00:15:28.940
besides KPIs, things that, you know, lead into that.

00:15:28.940 --> 00:15:34.299
And as crazy as it sounds, some organizations struggle to measure those.

00:15:34.299 --> 00:15:41.299
So, and to do so in a consistent and repeatable way, you know, so maybe they measure something

00:15:41.299 --> 00:15:46.380
that just comes from one person sitting at a desk, and they've done it for six years,

00:15:46.380 --> 00:15:48.900
and they leave, and now all of a sudden, you know, who knows how they do that.

00:15:48.900 --> 00:15:55.900
So just getting in a, creating a framework for consistent measurement is huge for an

00:15:55.900 --> 00:15:58.619
organization, right?

00:15:58.619 --> 00:16:04.820
If the measurement is consistent, outcomes are measured consistently, then taking action

00:16:04.820 --> 00:16:09.820
to improve those outcomes can be thought of as more reliable because the measurement process

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:11.859
is consistent.

00:16:11.859 --> 00:16:18.460
So that would be one thing for sure.

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:25.919
And I guess another, you know, on that note, it's decisioning, right?

00:16:25.919 --> 00:16:30.520
Every company makes decisions, and a lot of us are here because we like to do this

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:32.479
kind of work.

00:16:32.479 --> 00:16:37.799
But most of our companies exist because they like to make money, and they like to grow.

00:16:37.799 --> 00:16:43.640
And so we find a balance between, you know, doing what we do to help our company to achieve

00:16:43.640 --> 00:16:44.919
their goals.

00:16:44.919 --> 00:16:53.520
And so if you can find ways to help your company optimize cost and, you know, reduce waste

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:58.919
and increase growth, and again, all of that is through, you know, measuring and looking

00:16:58.919 --> 00:17:01.559
at decisions that have been made in the past and thinking about how they could have been

00:17:01.559 --> 00:17:07.880
made differently and doing historical analysis or building models to help make those decisions

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:11.680
more effectively, then that's obviously a huge win for any organization.

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:13.199
Thank you.

00:17:13.199 --> 00:17:17.959
Josh, I see you had asked a question in the chat.

00:17:17.959 --> 00:17:20.599
Do you want to jump in and maybe introduce yourself?

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:24.479
Because you'll be joining us as a featured leader in a few weeks here too.

00:17:24.479 --> 00:17:25.479
Sure.

00:17:25.479 --> 00:17:26.479
Thanks, Rachel.

00:17:26.479 --> 00:17:27.479
Yeah.

00:17:27.479 --> 00:17:28.479
So I'm Josh King.

00:17:28.479 --> 00:17:32.239
I'll be, I think, April 20th, I'll be a leader as well.

00:17:32.239 --> 00:17:35.640
And similar to you, Dan, I focus a lot on marketing data science.

